Taken with eorum vero qui sibi non liquere dixerunt sapientiam laudo in the last sentence (and homines sapientes, ἓ 76), this ought to be sufficient proof that the nine names which follow are those of the jurors who voted Non liquet. But this would give a minority of only fourteen (nine for ‘ Not Proven,' and five for acquittal) against eighteen for a conviction, whereas we are told in the pro Caecina, ἓ 29, that the issue depended on a single vote. The number of those who voted Non liquet must have been, not nine, but ten.
